title: Part 4
content:
Part 4

ABOUT 30 MINUTES before the Class B students were suddenly attacked.

At 11:00 a.m., Class C reached the first event time of the second day and upon receiving information that all squares on the outer perimeter had been designated as restricted areas, they immediately began a new strategy meeting.

Although the sea accounted for most of it, the fact that a total of 56 squares had become restricted left the students unable to hide their surprise.

"Does this mean the restricted areas might...grow from the outside in?"

As Hashimoto murmured his hypothesis, Morishita immediately added to it.

"That's a definite possibility. If the map ultimately shrinks to a single area, a fight will be inevitable. Don't you think Ayanokouji Kiyotaka would agree?"

It was a simple and effective way to forcibly gather the classes that'd been keeping their distance until then.

"I agree. Even if the map doesn't converge perfectly on the center, expanding the restricted areas from the perimeter inward is one of the most logical ways to lead us toward the end goal of this survival game: defeating opponents with paintball guns."

If all the remaining outer squares became unusable with each event, an additional 48 squares would be lost. On the third occasion, another 40 would disappear and by tomorrow, it would shrink to the final square. Considering the three-night, four-day duration, the pace of reduction would inevitably be a bit slower, but it was best to keep in mind that it would likely end up that way by the final day.

Northeast, northwest, southeast, southwest, or the center.

The probability that it would narrow from one of these points was high, but it was still impossible to determine which one for now.

Or rather, the school probably wouldn't narrow it down in a way that would be easy to figure out early on.

That was precisely why each class was racking their brains, trying to decide where to move while still participating in events.

The starting point wouldn't be revealed until the third day at the earliest, or perhaps at the time of reduction on the fourth day.

"Right now, everyone's focused on moving around the island, gathering supplies and staying healthy, but that's nothing more than a prelude. It's become more likely that the class that can secure the best position for the final firefight or the one that can seize even the slightest momentum, will be the victor."

"So it's like this whole thing's going to be settled with a pure survival game? Well then, I'm ready to show my stuff."

Morishita clenched her fist.

The possibility that the outcome would be decided by pure combat had indeed increased. No matter how many rounds of ammunition or how much food one gathered, a moment of carelessness could take out ten or twenty people. So what was the point of these three nights and four days? Of course, it served as a mechanism to create small advantages, but it seemed too elaborate for just that. Was it an opportunity to experience life on a deserted island and learn from the extraordinary? The food obtained from supply crates was by no means plentiful and they were forced to manage their health under difficult conditions, so gaining survival experience separate from the game itself wasn't a bad thing... but.

Was this survival embedded in a survival game, or a survival game embedded in survival?

Or would this lead to something completely separate from the special exam?

"It'd be great for us if the other classes just started fighting each other in the smaller area. No doubt we'll be at a disadvantage in a firefight if we don't close the numbers gap, even by a little."

Ignoring my classmates who continued their discussion, I narrowed down the possible scenarios to a few patterns and plotted them all out on the virtual map I'd already constructed in my mind.

The chaotic battle in the endgame was unavoidable. If the three VIPs were unfortunately taken out by stray rounds, it would be checkmate. On the other hand, if only the VIPs were to flee, their allies would lose contact with their commander and wouldn't know the enemy's location, which would also increase the risk of the VIPs being targeted and picked off. The existence of tactics for identifying individuals was likely a weapon for just such a situation.

In the end, even if I could wrack my brain and increase our odds of winning, I couldn't bring them to one hundred percent.

Still, I had to build a strategy to increase our chances of winning, even by a single percent.

How would the four classes move in response to the restricted areas? What're they planning?

I had to construct the logic and predict several outcomes.

I thought faster than anyone else about how I could intervene to reach the ideal outcome.

I deduced the psychological states of each class, considering the presence of the VIPs, their movements within the deep forest and where they would end up.

The future-oriented movements of Class A and Class D.

To what extent did Class B intend to suppress Class C?

Taking a composite view of all those factors, I first considered how my own class should move.

And then there was one other lingering concern: the likely route of Koenji, who moved freely and capriciously on his own. He was a presence that had surely been plaguing Horikita's mind from the start.

Thinking of it as a chance to provoke him and observe his movements, perhaps she would try to control him a little, even if it was a long shot.

While weaving together the event area displayed on the analyst's tablet and the reports from the commander, I raised my head to look at my classmates.

"We're leaving now. We're going to secure the supplies and food at G11."

Even if we ran, a fight would occur eventually. It was a decision to strike rather than wait.

Hearing that, my classmates looked at each other, their expressions showing a hint of confusion.

"It's tough that no supplies spawned in an area we can safely secure, but going for G11 means we'll run into Ryuuen's class, right? Besides, they're a little closer."

Matoba said he didn't like a gamble where, even if they headed out immediately, there was a chance the supplies could be collected first.

He continued, saying they should consider waiting and seeing for this event, but I strongly rejected that and reiterated that we would be going on the offensive.

"Enough idle talk. It's precisely because the enemy is closer that we must get there first."

Ryuuen's group would probably take ten to fifteen minutes, while it would take us fifteen to twenty.

Swift action was essential to close that five-minute gap.

"Ayanokouji's the leader. We trust him and follow his orders, right?"

"...Well... I guess so. All right."

Even with Hashimoto's words, Matoba couldn't seem to shake his anxiety, but that feeling itself wasn't wrong. After all, jumping into a place where the enemy was lying in wait was akin to a suicide mission.

I didn't address their unease and we began to move. At the GPS update five minutes later, all of us moved into area G12.

"Class B's GPS shows they're currently split into three groups. One group of ten is heading toward area E9. Another ten are in G8. And the rest are all gathered over by G11."

As I took the radio report, information regarding the other classes' situations was also relayed.

"So the real fight is finally starting, huh... Even though they're missing twenty-something people, that just barely makes us even. No, maybe I should just be grateful we can fight on even terms...?"

"That's not necessarily true. They've realized we're heading for G11 at this point, so they might just turn back and launch an all-out attack... What'll we do if we see signs of that?"

"That's unlikely to happen. Even if it looks like we're targeting G11, they can't gauge how serious we are. If they were to call back the group they sent to retrieve supplies, we would naturally retreat. They know that."

Class B, who could reach the target area first, gained an advantage at that point.

Being in a position to intercept us created a significant advantage. It wasn't too late for them to fight for real after they probed just how serious we were about capturing the supplies.

We rearranged our formation, solidifying the front to middle ranks with boys as guards. The two VIPs were placed in the back, I stood in front of them and Hashimoto took up the rear, as if to protect the VIPs' backs.

"Gotta admit, even I'm getting a little tense here."

Perhaps his weapon-holding hand was sweating, as Hashimoto supported his weapon with his left hand and lightly wiped his right on his jersey. Once he finished, he did the same with the other hand. The time was 11:15 a.m. I received the latest information and learned that the GPS signals of Ryuuen's group, lying in wait, were packed together just ahead. After that, I also received the routine report on the locations of the other GPS signals.

"They're just ahead... maybe two or three minutes... if we walk that far..."

I gave a hand signal, instructing everyone to stop.

"We'll wait here for five minutes."

"Five minutes? Is that okay? Won't they take the supplies during that time if we're not careful?"

"They don't have that luxury."

They were likely planning to lie in wait and intercept us with a flawless formation. If they carelessly focused on the supplies, their initial reaction to our attack would be delayed. Before long, our surroundings fell silent.

A silence to ensure we wouldn't miss the sound if, by some chance, they attacked first.

A time when only the tense breathing of my classmates echoed through the forest.

As time ticked by, feeling more like an hour than just five minutes, Shiraishi spoke in a low voice.

"There seems to be almost no movement. They're completely wary of us and have stopped. Shimazaki-kun says to let him know whenever you want to use a tactic."

"We're not using any tactics. If we save them, the enemy will have to remain constantly on guard. More importantly, tell me the GPS locations and details for the other classes."

I got looks from several people, as if asking why I needed information on other classes in that situation, but I got the details from the commander and had Shiraishi relay them to me.

"We'll wait another five minutes."

"...Seriously? Well... Roger."

How we would fight after that was already decided.

We could've attacked then and we could've attacked five minutes ago.

And—I already knew the result.

But, if we were going to attack anyway, it was better to do it at the ideal time.

We spent another five minutes in silence and the time passed 11:25 a.m. Immediately after confirming through Shiraishi that the targets ahead had barely moved and after receiving the status report on the other classes, I raised my arm.

"Let's advance. Once you find the enemy, you have my permission to attack without hesitation. Also, Matoba, you'll take command during the battle."

"What? Aren't you going to take command, Ayanokouji?"

"I thought it best to leave it to you in the front lines, for the sake of class coordination."

"...I see... In that case, I accept. Let's go...!"

It probably wasn't an appointment he was happy about, but Matoba accepted readily without arguing.

"Ayanokouji, you just stay back here and protect the VIPs, okay? As long as they're safe, I still think we can win this,"

Hashimoto said in a small voice, considering the possibility that Matoba might fail.

"Understood."

Matoba ran to the front, let out a word to fire everyone up and moved forward.

Immediately after, there was a loud cracking sound of a branch breaking in the woods ahead—

Right after, a series of gunshots that seemed to rip through the forest air flew at us.

The bullets tore through the air and leaves scattered, leaving behind the specks of paintballs.

Several people in the front line flinched, their shoulders trembling.

The enemy's first strike. Class B spotted us first and made their move.

"They're firing! Fire! Light 'em up!"

It didn't go like it did in practice; the students kept their fingers on the triggers and fired on full auto.

The return fire split thin branches diagonally, leaving marks like blood splatters with every impact.

But hitting them wasn't easy. The distance was still fifteen to twenty meters or more.

The enemy had taken up positions between the trees and rocks and only small parts of their faces and bodies were visible.

Just when they were spotted, they immediately pulled back and returned fire when they saw an opening.

"Three to the front right! I've confirmed one more in the back!"

"Hold them down! Concentrate fire on the base of that tree!"

At Matoba's command, the front line fired all at once.

Paintballs flew in succession, chipping away at the tree's bark.

However—the alarm that was supposed to sound from a wristwatch upon a successful hit never went off.

On the contrary, a counterattack came back immediately.

An enemy's shot flew in as if sliding from a low angle, striking one of the Class C vanguards squarely in the chest. Bright red paint spread as an electronic sound rang out.

"One person's out! Fall back a bit!"

"Shit, where the hell are they shooting from!?"

Panic spread in an instant. Not missing this opportunity, Class B laid down a barrage from the cover of the woods on both sides.

A dozen or so dry popping sounds rang out in succession. The formation fell into disarray and the situation was disastrous.

"Ugh—!"

A second and then a third, were hit in quick succession.

Unable to expose their bodies to defend themselves, they were taken out one after another, starting with those with the largest exposed areas.

Hashimoto immediately shouted, the smile completely gone from his face.

"Front line, fall back to the trees and use the cover better! Mid-rank, provide covering fire!"

The students moved according to the orders, but the trees were close together and visibility was poor.

Class B's shots were clearly more accurate than ours; they read our positions and adjusted their angles of attack.

Even so, one of the shots they returned miraculously hit its mark.

A faint electronic sound rang out from deep within the forest and one of the opponents stood up.

In that moment, the atmosphere on our side shifted slightly.

"A hit! We took one down!"

"Nice, keep 'em pinned down!"

The rhythm of their firing returned for just a moment.

But the enemy also regrouped immediately.

Matching our gunfire, they fired back with precision, as if pinpointing our locations by sound.

A paintball grazed past someone's head and spectacularly splattered a tree behind them.

"Three to the front left! There's another guy aiming from deep in the woods!"

"It's too dangerous to circle around, keep your distance!"

An order was given, but a student on the right couldn't react in time and was shot in the shoulder, triggering the fourth electronic sound.

Then another, someone who had been behind a tree, was shot in the leg and the 'out' signal rang.

A fifth person. Deeply colored paint dripped onto the ground.

The firefight lasted only a few minutes, but it was so intense it left them breathless.

"I'm hit! I can't even tell if we're hitting them at all!"

A student, crouching to stay out of the way, punched the ground in frustration.

"No, we hit 'em! My shot hit just now!"

"On the right side, there's five of them!"

I took a moment to compose my breathing and surveyed the scene before me.

Class B remained hidden in the shade of the trees. The tempo of their shooting didn't falter.

They probably had the advantage of having secured more paintballs than Class C with their provisions, but the difference in quality was clear.

Even if the numbers were equal, Class B was overwhelmingly superior in terms of supplies, momentum and composure. That much was clear even just watching from a short distance away.

Compared to our casualties, the enemy had at most one or two.

If it continued, our losses would only grow.

It was safe to conclude that the outcome of the battle had been decided in an instant.

Calmly and briefly, I gave the order.

"Continuing any further will only worsen our losses. We're retreating."

"R-Retreat? We're retreating, right!?"

I announced the retreat to all the remaining classmates and had the front line fall back by walking backward so they would not be pursued. It was then that Morishita also hurried from the middle line to the rear.

A Class B student closed in, their gun's muzzle taking aim at Morishita.

"Watch out, Yamamura Miki—"

Morishita shouted and just as she grabbed both of Yamamura's shoulders, a single paintball hit her in the back.

"Kgh...!"

An expression of anguish. Immediately after, a second and then a third shot landed on her back.

Hashimoto hurriedly fired back but missed and the Class B student retreated as if to flee.

"Ugh..."

A groan. Morishita was done for now, the alarm on her wrist blaring mercilessly.

"M-Morishita-san!"

"It would appear... this is the end for me. At the very least, you must escape..."

"No... Why would you protect someone like me...!?"

No, had Morishita really protected Yamamura? It looked to me like the gun had been aimed at Morishita and realizing she was the target, she had tried to use the nearby Yamamura as a shield to save herself, but failed... No, surely even Morishita wouldn't do something like that— Actually, she just might.

"I, too, had some goodness left in my heart. That is all there is to it."

Whichever her true intentions were, there was no time to find out now.

"You must live, Yamamura Miki. And, in my stead, as an Amazoness... Ghk."

"Morishita-san...Morishita-san..."

Morishita had closed her eyes and leaned limply, but then she suddenly snapped them wide open.

"I believe it would be best for you to flee quickly. Pursuers may be on their way."

"Eh, ah... Um, that is, yes..."

"Ayanokouji Kiyotaka. I leave the rest to you. I shall be taking it easy on the ship."

For someone who'd just been eliminated, she didn't seem to mind at all. In fact, she even seemed happy that things had wrapped up so quickly.

And so, the 'Amazoness of the Dense Forest' who even volunteered to be a guard was out, disappearing from the class without making any major contribution.

At the very end, a strange, relaxed atmosphere hung in the air for a moment, but we hurried to continue our retreat regardless.
